I. INTRODUCTION\
\
A recent study (Mayer) found that over 80 percent of the Quantcast U.S. top 250 websites were "leaky" -- they surveilled or passed along personally identifiable information (PII) of the user through the often-invisible mechanisms of cookies, supercookies, or browser fingerprinting. Similarly, a 2009 study saw that web bugs were "ubiquitous" (Gomez, Pinnick & Soltani, 2009). Compounding the issue, these harvested data are  often given or sold to third parties that are not contactable or controllable by the original user. This aggregation and permanent storage can result in loss of privacy and political control, exposure to hackers and scammers, or even getting on a telemarketer list.\
\
In addition the tracking may be opaque, and beyond the user's ability to consent to. When a user places items in a shopping cart, or checks a "Remember Me" box, there exists a transactional relationship in which the user has opened the kimono slightly in exchange for a certain functionality, but many sites automatically place cookies, check a browser fingerprint, or use other invisible methods to gather data on the user. And the surveillance may be by a third party, which the user would never have entered into any relationship with. If Web Site X has ancillary relationships with other services that load invisible tracking tools, the user cannot make an informed assessment of this third party's trustworthiness or reliability. This is along the lines of what Marx (2006) termed "soft surveillance" and "mandatory volunteerism": you can opt not to give up privacy, but you're barred from the common.  \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\pardirnatural
\cf0 Technically adept users have long had the option of changing browser settings, deleting individual cookies, or browsing using anonymizing tools, though this is a small subset of internet users and not a generalized solution. Some sites offer "opt-out" cookies and there is the recent development of "do not track" tools, with the goal of stopping such surveillance (the latter even knowingly echoes the name of the Federal Trade Commission's (FTC) Do Not Call registry). However, there is no structure in place to monitor whether sites honor these, leavings users, in terms of surveilling the surveillers. \
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\pardirnatural
\cf0 \
Due to this opacity (or even invisibility), people cannot resist or judge whether surveillance is worthwhile or illegitimate without this awareness; trust and confidence in parties even in consentual actions are in a state of unstable equilibrium when full disclosure can destroy the dyad. \
\
And users are lacking a basic level of control over their personal information -- they cannot even begin to consider any of the "standard means of redress" such as obfuscation or other forms of protest (Brunton & Nissenbaum, 2011). This is especially problematic in light of Helen Nissenbaum's framework of "contextual integrity" as being necessary for people if they want to manage their privacy. And, as Marx (2003) pointed out, "a lack of resistance to intrusive surveillance may mask as acceptance". \
\
Our work on Tracking Report Card hopes to surface the hidden pipelines of personal information tracking and be the first user-friendly tool to track if sites and third parties adhere to the the user's choice of opting out or requesting not to be tracked. The Tracking Report Card tool is a browser extension that alerts users if the site they visit uses third-party tracking cookies and grades both this first-party site and any third-party sites involved based on their "good citizenship" around respecting opt-out and Do Not Track requests. Though currently the Tracking Report Card does not have comprehensive data about every site on the internet, our base of the Alexa top 500 United States sites is a strong starting point.\
\
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\pardirnatural
\cf0 Our project does not necessarily lead to nor rely on resistance or non-compliance by the user. But it creates the conceptual space between the online content desired by the user, and the tracking infrastructure that currently is the invisible substrate. \
\
Though the initial concern in our work was on tracking across popular (commercial) web sites, we can see how many of the practices and privacy issues our project scores could also be applied in political contexts -- Pfaffenberger (1992) noted that technological practices can have great applications to and effect on the construction of political power as well as the resistance to political power. \
