II. USER CONCERNS & KNOWLEDGE\
\
Gomez, Pinnick, & Soltani (2009) combined and compared results from a range of general-public surveys and found that though there was widespread concern from users about the collection of personal data and profiling, they admitted little to no knowledge  of the details or processes, or even when it occurred. And when investigating more specific elements of user complaints to the FTC relevant to the General Privacy (GP) and Gramm-Leach-Bliley (GLB) statute codes, the researchers found that 39% of total privacy complaints were related to companies either not offering the opportunity to opt out, or not honoring the user's request to opt out. \
\
From these data, we can see that users want to know when personal data are collected (though do not know how to), want to know they can opt out of this tracking, and want to know if their decisions to opt out are effective.\
\
We attempt to address these concerns with the Tracking Report Card. The overall "grade" of both the first-party web page (the one the user has intentionally loaded) and the third-party services are determined by:\
\
1. whether the third-party site uses tracking cookies\
2. whether they offer an opt-out\
3. whether they delete the tracking cookie when the user opts out\
4. whether they add tracking cookies when you opt out\
5. and whether they delete the tracking cookies when you send the Do Not Track header\
\
As important as having this data is having it in a format understandable to the user. This is why we designed the Tracking Report Card as a browser extension so that it provides concurrent discovery: As a web page is displayed, it offers visually, and in plain language, the knowledge that your personal information is being collected. Linking the first-party site with alerts about its privacy "grade" not only synchronously but within the same browser is far more effective than requiring the user to enter the same URL into two different browser windows (or into a separate application) and switch between the two. \
\
We also tried to address a range of users with the column view layout of the browser extension. The leftmost column provides a summation (including a visual "grade" for the first-party web page), which gives an at-a-glance alert that the visited page has third-party tracking cookies. The center column shows a list of these (the list itself gives a visual cue as to whether there are a few or many of these); interested users can click on any of the list to see detailed information, such as TKTKTKTK. This is a familiar and welcome pattern to advanced users, similar to nested menus in applications.\
